section.p:
Queries are issued in the SDK using the query operation. This API accepts a
                string which is the statement to execute, and returns the rows (or an iterable
                object which returns rows) representing the query’s result. Here is an example of a
                query executed in
                Python:>>> for row in cb.n1ql_query('SELECT type FROM `travel-sample` LIMIT 4'):
...   print(row)
... 
{'type': 'airline'}
{'type': 'airline'}
{'type': 'airline'}
{'type': 'airport'}

The above query using cbq (some output truncated for
                clarity):cbq> SELECT type FROM `travel-sample` LIMIT 4;
{
    ...
    "results": [
        {
            "type": "airport"
        },
        {
            "type": "airport"
        },
        {
            "type": "airport"
        },
        {
            "type": "airport"
        }
    ],
    "status": "success",
    "metrics": {
    ...
    }
}

If you use aliases in your query, then the returned rows contained the aliased name
                rather than the original name. For
                example:>>> for row in cb.n1ql_query('SELECT airportname as n FROM `travel-sample` where type="airport" LIMIT 4'):
...   print(row)
... 
{'n': 'Calais Dunkerque'}
{'n': 'Peronne St Quentin'}
{'n': 'Les Loges'}
{'n': 'Couterne'}

body.section:
Specifying query criteria
N1QL's true strength is the ability to
                query documents satisfying given criteria, querying for documents whose properties
                evaluate to certain values or expressions. Specifying criteria is done much in the
                same manner as in SQL: Using a WHERE clause. Multiple conditions can be specified
                using the AND or OR keywords.
The following
                example selects all documents that have a type of airport
                and have a city of
                Reno.cbq> SELECT airportname, city, country FROM `travel-sample` WHERE type="airport" AND city="Reno";
{
    ...
    "results": [
        {
            "airportname": "Reno Tahoe Intl",
            "city": "Reno",
            "country": "United States"
        }
    ],
    "status": "success",
    "metrics": {
    ...
    }
}Note
            that you should use query placeholders, as it is not only more secure, but also
            allows your query to be prepared and optimized for reuse.

